@NODE WindowFallback "WindowFallback"

@{b}NAME@{ub}
Windowfallback

@{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
Windowfallback <ScreenID> <Window> <left> <top> <Num> <Fractalname>

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
Closes the window and opens it again on the scren defined by the <SceenID>.

@{b}INPUT PARAMETERS@{ub}
<Window> may contain any of the following strings:
            PicTask    Palette    Anim1    Anim2
            User       Parm1      Parm2    Parm3
            Data       ShowLoc    ShowJul  Parm3D1
            Parm3D2    Parm3D3    Formula  CycleControl

<Num>         : Only needed, if <Window>=User. In this case <Num> specifies the
                number of the user defined window.
<Fractalname> : Must  be  specified,  if  <Window> = Parm1, Parm2, Parm3, Data,
                ShowLoc, ShowJul, Parm3D1, Parm3D2 or Parm3D3.
<left>,<top>  : left  top  corner  in  the virtual coordinates  system with the
                resolution of 10000x10000 pixel.
                Negative values ==> use defaultvalues
<ScreenID>    : specifies the screen, the window should open on:
                0 - on the fractalscreen
                1 - on the parameterscreen (eventually opened)
                2 - on the workbench
                3 - on the public screen, specified in the preferences program

@{b}RESULTS@{ub}
RC:
 5 ... fractal unknown or <Window> unknown
 8 ... wrong number of parameters, or <Window> unknown
Result:
 N.A.

@{b}BUGS@{ub}
The errors can be somehow confusing under some circumstances. If <Window> is un-
equal to PicTask, Palette, Anim1, Anim2 and User, then the program thinks,  that
a fractal must be specified. If no additional parameter is specified,  then  the
routine returns RC=8, for example the following call:

WindowFallback 2 "PALETTEN" 5000 5000

PALETTEN is a slight mistake, should be PALETTE, but the program says 'not enough
parameters' (?) ...

@{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
---

@ENDNODE

@NODE Windowtype "Windowtype"

@{b}NAME@{ub}
WindowType

@{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
WindowType <Fractalname> <Backdrop>

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
Specifies the windowtype. <Backdrop> determines, whether is should be a backdrop-
window.

@{b}INPUT PARAMETERS@{ub}
<Fractalname> : Name of the fractal
<Backdrop>    : 1 ==> window should be a backdropwindow, 0 ==> window should be a
                normal window with border, sizegadget, etc.

@{b}RESULTS@{ub}
RC:
 3 ... fractal not calculated
 5 ... fractal unknown
 8 ... wrong number of parameters
Result:
 N.A.

@{b}BUGS@{ub}
---

@{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
---

@ENDNODE

@NODE Zoom "Zoom"

@{b}NAME@{ub}
Zoom

@{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
Zoom <Fractalname> <PosX> <PosY> <Faktor> <Frames>

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
This command makes the same as a double click onto a place of the window.

@{b}INPUT PARAMETERS@{ub}
<Fractalname>    : Name of the fractal
<PosX>
<PosY>           : Specify  the  place in the  virtual coordinates system of the
                   size 10000x10000 , i.e. PosX=5000, PosY=5000 means the mid of
                   the window, independent of the actual size of the window.
<Faktor>         : Specifies  the  zooming factor, greater than 1 means zoom in,
                   values between 0 and 1 zoom out. The  maximum and minimum for
                   this value are 0.5 and 2. Values,  which  exceeds this range,
                   are brought to the nearest extremevalue.
<Frames>         : Specifies,  how  often  the  content of the window is scaled.
                   Minimum is 0, maximum is 20.

@{b}RESULTS@{ub}
RC:
 3 ... fractal not calculated
 5 ... fractal unknown
 8 ... wrong number of parameters
Result:
 N.A.

@{b}BUGS@{ub}
---

@{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
---

@ENDNODE


